    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1934-07-27T14:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1934-07-27T14:00:00-05:00" n="331"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d331">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">611.3831/61: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Minister in Haiti</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Armour</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Port-au-Prince</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1934-07-27T14:00:00-05:00"
                            >July 27, 1934—2 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received 2:45 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>81. Department’s telegram No. 68, July 26, 3 p.m. My idea in having De la Rue
                    proceed August 2 was not only for commercial treaty negotiations but the
                    importance of having him available during August for possible conference with
                    National City Bank<note n="33" xml:id="d331fn33">See <ref target="#pg_339">pp.
                            339</ref> ff.</note> particularly during absence of Perkins<note n="34"
                        xml:id="d331fn34">J. H. Perkins, Chairman of the Board of the National City
                        Bank.</note> and Lancaster<note n="35" xml:id="d331fn35">William W.
                        Lancaster, Counsel for the National City Bank.</note> in Europe. I have
                    spoken to the Haitian Government on this latter phase and both the President and
                    the Minister of Foreign Affairs feel he should be available for any discussion
                    with bankers that may arise as a result of possible modifications in contract as
                    well as to assist Blanchet later when our Government is ready to begin
                    preliminary conversations looking towards commercial <pb facs="0382" n="316"
                        xml:id="pg_316"/> treaty. I hope the Department will therefore have no
                    objection to his proceeding August 2. Please instruct.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Armour</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
